\pard\plain\s2\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs40\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 Introduction\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 {This is a first attempt} to provide some written material of a course in mathemathical methods of theoretical physics. I am presenting this course to an undergraduate audience at the Vienna University of Technology. Only God knows (see Ref. 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_Aquinas \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{12}{1981}{{Aquinas}}{{}}}}}
] part one, question 14, article 13; and also Ref. 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_specker_60 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{124}{1960}{{Specker}}{{}}}}}
], p. 243) if I manage to teach them the subject!  I kindly ask the perplexed to please be patient, do not panic under any circumstances, and do not allow themselves to be too upset with mistakes, omissions & other problems of this text. At the end of the day, everything will be fine, and in the long run we will be dead anyway.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {I am releasing this} text to the public domain because it is my conviction and experience that content can no longer be held back, and access to it be restricted, as its creators see fit. On the contrary, we experience a push toward so much content that we can hardly bear this information flood, so we have to be selective and restrictive rather than aquisitive. I hope that there are some readers out there who actually enjoy and profit from the text, in whatever form and way they find appropriate.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {My own encounter} with many researchers of different fields and different degrees of formalization has convinced me that there is no single way of formally comprehending a subject 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_anderson_73 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{10}{1972}{{Anderson}}{{}}}}}
]. With regards to formal rigour, there appears to be a rather questionable chain of contempt \endash  all too often theoretical physicists suspiciously look down at the experimentalists, mathematical physicists suspiciously look down at the theoreticians, and mathematicians suspiciously look down at the mathematical physicists. I have even experienced the doubts formal logicians expressed about their collegues in mathematics!  For an anectodal evidence, take the claim of a very prominant member of the mathematical physics community, who once dryly remarked in front of a fully packed audience, \ldblquote what other people call \lquote proof\rquote  I call \lquote conjecture\rquote ! \rdblquote \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {So please be aware} that not all I present here will be acceptable to everybody; for various reasons. Some people will claim that I am too confusing and utterly formalistic, others will claim my arguments are in desparate need of rigour. Many formally fascinated readers will demand to go deeper into the meaning of the subjects; others may want some easy-to-identify pragmatic, syntactic rules of deriving results. I apologise to both groups from the onset. This is the best I can do; from certain different perspectives, others, maybe even some tutors or students, might perform much better.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {I am calling} for a greater unity in physics; as well as for a greater esteem on \ldblquote both sides of the same effort;\rdblquote  I am also opting for more pragmatism; one that acknowledges the mutual benefits and oneness of theoretical and empirical physical world perceptions. Schr\u1094?dinger 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_schroed_natgr \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{117}{1954}{{Schr{\'f6}dinger}}{{}}}}}
] cites Democritus with arguing against a too great separation of the intellect ({}, dianoia) and the senses ({}, aitheseis). In fragment D 125 from Galen 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_Diels_fdv \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{39}{1906}{{Diels}}{{}}}}}
], p. 408, footnote 125 , the intellect claims \ldblquote ostensibly there is color, ostensibly sweetness, ostensibly bitterness, actually only atoms and the void;\rdblquote  to which the senses retort: \ldblquote Poor intellect, do you hope to defeat us while from us you borrow your evidence?  Your victory is your defeat.\rdblquote  {German: Nachdem D. [[Demokritos]] sein Mi\'dftrauen gegen die Sinneswahrnehmungen in dem Satze ausgesprochen: \lquote Scheinbar (d. i. konventionell) ist Farbe, scheinbar S\'fc\'dfigkeit, scheinbar Bitterkeit: wirklich nur Atome und Leeres\rdblquote  l\'e4\'dft er die Sinne gegen den Verstand reden: \lquote Du armer Verstand, von uns nimmst du deine Beweisst\'fccke und willst uns damit besiegen?  Dein Sieg ist dein Fall! \rquote }\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {Professor ernst Specker} from the ETH Z\'fcrich once remarked that, of the many books of David Hilbert, most of them carry his name first, and the name(s) of his co-author(s) appear second, although the subsequent author(s) had actually written these books; the only exception of this rule being Courant and Hilbert\rquote s 1924 book {\i Methoden der mathematischen Physik}, comprising around 1000 densly packed pages, which allegedly none of these authors had really written. It appears to be some sort of collective effort of scholars from the University of G\'f6ttingen.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {So, in sharp distinction} from these comprehensive efforts, I most humbly present my own version of what is important for standard courses of contemporary physics. Thereby, I am quite aware that, not dissimilar with some attempts of that sort undertaken so far, I might fail miserably. Because even if I manage to induce some interest, affaction, passion and understanding in the audience \endash  as Danny Greenberger put it, inevitably four hundred years from now, all our present physical theories of today will appear transient 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_lakatosch \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{78}{1978}{{Lakatos}}{{}}}}}
], if not laughable. And thus in the long run, my efforts will be forgotten; and some other brave, courageous guy will continue attempting to (re)present the most important mathematical methods in theoretical physics.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {Having in mind} this saddening piece of historic evidence, and for as long as we are here on Earth, let us carry on and start doing what we are supposed to be doing well; just as Krishna in Chapter XI:32,33 of the {\scaps0\b0\i Bhagavad Gita} is quoted for insisting upon Arjuna to fight, telling him to {\i \ldblquote stand up, obtain glory!  Conquer your enemies, acquire fame and enjoy a prosperous kingdom. All these warriors have already been destroyed by me. You are only an instrument.\rdblquote }\par
{\pard\plain\s9\qc\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 { \fs50 } \par
