\pard\plain\s2\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs40\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 Unreasonable effectiveness of mathematics in the natural sciences\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 All things considered, it is mind-boggling why formalized thinking and numbers utilize our comprehension of nature. Even today people muse about the unreasonable effectiveness of mathematics in the natural sciences 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_wigner \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{139}{1960}{{Wigner}}{{}}}}}
].\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 Zeno of Elea and Parmenides, for instance, wondered how there can be motion, either in universe which is infinitely divisible, or discrete. Because, in the dense case, the slightest finite move would require an infinity of actions. Likewise in the discrete case, how can there be motion if everything is not moving at all times 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_zeno \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{82}{1936}{{Lee}}{{}}}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_benna_62 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{18}{1962}{{Benacerraf}}{{}}}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_gruenbaum_68 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{59}{1968}{{Gr{\'fc}nbaum}}{{}}}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_Sainsbury \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{109}{2009}{{Sainsbury}}{{}}}}}
]? \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 A related question regards the physical limit state of a hypothetical lamp, considered by Thomson 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_thom_54 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{130}{1954}{{Thomson}}{{}}}}}
], with ever decreasing switching cycles. For the sake of perplexion, take Neils Henrik Abel\rquote s verdict denouncing that (Letter to Holmboe, January 16, 1826 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_Hardy_1949 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{61}{1949}{{Hardy}}{{}}}}}
]), {\i \ldblquote divergent series are the invention of the devil, and it is shameful to base on them any demonstration whatsoever.\rdblquote } This, of course, did neither prevent Abel nor too many other discussants to investigate these devilish inventions.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 If one encodes the physical states of the Thomson lamp by \ldblquote 0\rdblquote  and \ldblquote 1,\rdblquote  associated with the lamp \ldblquote on\rdblquote  and \ldblquote off,\rdblquote  respectively, and the switching process with the concatenation of \ldblquote +1\rdblquote  and \ldblquote -1\rdblquote  performed so far, then the divergent infinite series associated with the Thomson lamp is the Leibniz series {\par
\pard\plain\s12\ql\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\tqc\tx3450\tqr\tx6900\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 \tab
\tab{\b0 ({\*\bkmkstart BM2009_fiftyfifty_1}1{\*\bkmkend BM2009_fiftyfifty_1})}\par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 which is just a particular instance of a geometric series (see below) with the common ratio \ldblquote -1.\rdblquote  Here, \ldblquote A\rdblquote  indicates the Abel sum 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_Hardy_1949 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{61}{1949}{{Hardy}}{{}}}}}
] obtained from a \ldblquote continuation\rdblquote  of the geometric series, or alternatively, by {}.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 As this shows, formal sums of the Leibnitz type ({\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BM2009_fiftyfifty_1 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{1.1}}}) require specifications which could make them unique. But has this \ldblquote specification by continuation\rdblquote  any kind of physical meaning? \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 In modern days, similar arguments have been translated into the proposal for infinity machines by Blake 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_Blake26 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{23}{1926}{{Blake}}{{}}}}}
], p. 651, and Weyl 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_weyl_49 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{137}{1949}{{Weyl}}{{}}}}}
], pp. 41-42, which could solve many very difficult problems by searching through unbounded recursively enumerable cases. To achive this physically, ultrarelativistic methods suggest to put observers in \ldblquote fast orbits\rdblquote  or throw them toward black holes 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_pit_90 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{99}{1990}{{Pitowsky}}{{}}}}}
].\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 The Pythagoreans are often cited to have believed that the universe is natural numbers or simple fractions thereof, and thus physics is just a part of mathematics; or that there is no difference between these realms. They took their conception of numbers and world-as-numbers so seriously that the existence of irrational numbers which cannot be written as some ratio of integers shocked them; so much so that they allegedly drowned the poor guy who had discovered this fact. That is a typical case in which the metaphysical belief in one\rquote s own construction of the world overwhelms critical thinking; and what should be wisely taken as an epistemic finding is taken to be ontologic truth.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 The connection between physics and formalism has been debated by Bridgman 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_bridgman \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{29}{1934}{{Bridgman}}{{}}}}}
], Feynman 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_feynman_computation \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{48}{1996}{{Feynman}}{{}}}}}
], and Landauer 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_landauer \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{79}{1991}{{Landauer}}{{}}}}}
], among many others. The question, for instance, is imminent whether we should take the formalism very serious and literal, using it as a guide to new territories, which might even appear absurd, inconsistent and mind-boggling; just like {\i Alice\rquote s Adventures in Wonderland.} Should we expect that all the wild things formally imaginable have a physical realization? \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 Note that the formalist Hilbert 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_hilbert_26 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{67}{1926}{{Hilbert}}{{}}}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_cantor_set \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{35}{1895}{{Cantor}}{{}}}}}
], p. 170, is often quoted as claiming that nobody shall ever expel mathematicians from the paradise created by Cantor\rquote s set theory. {German original: {\i \ldblquote Aus dem Paradies, das Cantor uns geschaffen, soll uns niemand vertreiben k\'f6nnen.\rdblquote }} In Cantor\rquote s \ldblquote naive set theory\rdblquote  definition, \ldblquote a set is a collection into a whole of definite distinct objects of our intuition or of our thought. The objects are called the elements (members) of the set.\rdblquote  {Cantor\rquote s German original: \ldblquote Unter einer \ldblquote Menge\rdblquote  verstehen wir jede Zusammenfassung {} von bestimmten wohlunterschiedenen Objekten {} unsrer Anschauung oder unseres Denkens (welche die \ldblquote Elemente\rdblquote  von {} genannt werden) zu einem Ganzen.\rdblquote } If one allows substitution and self-reference 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_smullyan_78 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{121}{1992{a}}{{Smullyan}}{{}}}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_smullyan_92 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{122}{1992{b}}{{Smullyan}}{{}}}}}
], this definition turns out to be inconsistent; that is self-contradictory \endash  for instance Russel\rquote s paradoxical \ldblquote set of all sets that are not members of themselves\rdblquote  qualifies as set in the Cantorian approach. In praising the set theoretical paradise, Hilbert must have been well aware of the inconsistencies and problems that plagued Cantorian style set theory, but he fully dissented and refused to abandon its stimulus.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 Is there a similar pathos also in theoretical physics? \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 Maybe our physical capacities are limited by our mathematical fantasy alone?  Who knows? \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 For instance, could we make use of the Banach-Tarski paradox 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_springerlink_10_1007_BF03023740 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{50}{1988}{{French}}{{}}}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_wagon1 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{134}{1986}{{Wagon}}{{}}}}}
] as a sort of ideal production line?  The Banach-Tarski paradox makes use of the fact that in the continuum \ldblquote it is (nonconstructively) possible\rdblquote  to transform any given volume of three-dimensional space into any other desired shape, form and volume \endash  in particular also to double the original volume \endash  by transforming finite subsets of the original volume through isometries, that is, distance preserving mappings such as translations and rotations. This, of course, could also be perceived as a merely abstract paradox of infinity, somewhat similar to Hilbert\rquote s hotel.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 By the way, Hilbert\rquote s hotel 
