\pard\plain\s2\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs40\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 Methodology and proof methods\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 {For many theorems} there exist many proofs. For instance, the 4th edition of {\i Proofs from THE BOOK} 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_ziegler_aigner \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{4}{1998-2010}{{Aigner and Ziegler}}{{}}}}}
] lists six proofs of the infinity of primes (chapter 1). Chapter 19 refers to nearly a hundred proofs of the fundamental theorem of algebra, that every nonconstant polynomial with complex coefficients has at least one root in the field of complex numbers.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {Which proofs,} if there exist many, somebody choses or prefers is often a question of taste and elegance, and thus a subjective decision. Some proofs are constructive 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_bridges_richman \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{28}{1987}{{Bridges and Richman}}{{}}}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_bishop \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{22}{1985}{{Bishop and Bridges}}{{}}}}}
] and computable 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_aberth_80 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{1}{1980}{{Aberth}}{{}}}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_Weihrauch \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{135}{2000}{{Weihrauch}}{{}}}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_BHW08 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{27}{2008}{{Brattka et\~al.}}{{Brattka, Hertling, and Weihrauch}}}}}
] in the sense that a construction method is presented. Tractability is not an entirely completely different issue 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_kreisel \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{75}{1974}{{Kreisel}}{{}}}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_gandy2 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{51}{1980}{{Gandy}}{{}}}}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_pit_90 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{99}{1990}{{Pitowsky}}{{}}}}}
] \endash  note that even \ldblquote higher\rdblquote  polynomial growth of temporal or space and memory resources of a computation with some parameter may result in a solution which is unattainable \ldblquote for all practical purposes\rdblquote  (fapp) 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_bell_a \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{16}{1990}{{Bell}}{{}}}}}
].\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {For those of us} with a rather limited amount of storage and memory, and with a lot of troubles and problems, is is quite consolating that it is not (always) necessary to be able to memorize all the proofs that are necessary for the deduction of a particular corollary or theorem which turns out to be useful for the physical task at hand. In some cases, though, it may be necessary to keep in mind the assumptions and derivation methods that such results are based upon. For example, how many readers may be able to immediately derive the simple power rule for derivation of polynomials \endash  that is, for any real coefficient {}, the derivative is given by {}?  Most of us would acknowledge to be aware of, and be able and happy to apply, this rule.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {Let us just list} some concrete examples of the perplexing varieties of proof methods used today.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 For the sake of listing a mathematical proof method which does not have any \ldblquote constructive\rdblquote  or algorithmic flavour, consider a proof of the following theorem: {\i \ldblquote There exist irrational numbers {} with {}.\rdblquote }\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {\cf80 \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {Consider the following proof:}\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 case 1: {}; \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 case 2: {}, then {}.\par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 The proof assumes the {\i law of the excluded middle,} which excludes all other cases but the two just listed. The question of which one of the two cases is correct; that is, which number is rational, remains unsolved in the context of the proof. \endash  Actually, a proof that case 2 is correct and {} is a transcendential was only found by Gelfond and Schneider in 1934!  {The Gelfond-Schneider theorem states that, if {} and {} are algebraic numbers that is, if {} and {} are roots of a non-zero polynomial in one variable with rational or equivalently, integer, coefficients with {} and if {} is not a rational number, then any value of {} is a transcendental number.}\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {A typical proof by contradiction} is about the irrationality of {}.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {\cf80 \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 Suppose that {} is rational (false); that is {} for some {}. Suppose further that {} and {} are coprime; that is, they have no common positive divisor other than 1 or, equivalently, if their greatest common divisor is 1. Squaring the (wrong) assumption {} yields {} and thus {}. We have two different cases: either {} is odd, or {} is even. \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 case 1: suppose that {} is odd; that is {} for some {}; and thus {} is again odd (the square of an even number is again odd); but that cannot be, since {} equals {} and thus should be even; hence we arrive at a contradiction. \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 case 2: suppose that {} is even; that is {} for some {}; and thus {} or {}. Now observe that by assumption, {} cannot be even (remember {} and {} are coprime, and {} is assumed to be even), so {} must be odd. By the same argument as in case 1 (for odd n), we arrive at a contradiction. By combining these two exhaustive cases 1 & 2, we arrive at a complete contradiction; the only consistent alternative being the irrationality of {}.\par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {Still another issue} is whether it is better to have a proof of a \ldblquote true\rdblquote  mathematical statement rather than none. And what is truth \endash  can it be some revelation, a rare gift, such as seemingly in Sr\u299iniv\u257asa Aiyang\u257ar R\u257am\u257anujan\rquote s case? \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {There exist ancient} and yet rather intuitive \endash  but sometimes distracting and errorneous \endash  informal notions of proof. An example\~
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_baats1 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{14}{1988}{{Baaz}}{{}}}}}
] is the Babylonian notion to \ldblquote prove\rdblquote  arithmetical statements {\xe{\v Babylonian \ldblquote proof\rdblquote }} by considering \ldblquote large number\rdblquote  cases of algebraic formulae such as (Chapter V of Ref. 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_neugeb \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{96}{1934}{{Neugebauer}}{{}}}}}
]), \par
\pard\plain\s11\ql\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\tqc\tx3450\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 \tab
\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 As naive and silly this Babylonian \ldblquote proof\rdblquote  method may appear at first glance \endash  for various subjective reasons (e.g. you may have some suspicions with regards to particular deductive proofs and their results; or you simply want to check the correctness of the deductive proof) it can be used to \ldblquote convince\rdblquote  students and ourselves that a result which has derived deductively is indeed applicable and viable. We shall make heavy use of these kind of intuitive examples. As long as one always keeps in mind that this inductive, merely anecdotal, method is necessary but not sufficient (sufficiency is, for instance, guaranteed by complete induction) it is quite all right to go ahead with it.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 Another altogether different issue is knowledge acquired by revelation or by some authority. Oracles occur in modern computer science, but only as idealized concepts whose physical realization is highly questionable if not forbidden.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {Let us} shortly enumerate some proof methods, among others: {\par
\pard\plain\s46\ql\fi-283\li283\lin283\sb0\sa120\widctlpar\tql\tx283\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb50 \li600\fi-300 1.\tab
(indirect) proof by contradiction; \par
\pard\plain\s46\ql\fi-283\li283\lin283\sb0\sa120\widctlpar\tql\tx283\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb50 \li600\fi-300 2.\tab
proof by mathematical induction; \par
\pard\plain\s46\ql\fi-283\li283\lin283\sb0\sa120\widctlpar\tql\tx283\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb50 \li600\fi-300 3.\tab
direct proof; \par
\pard\plain\s46\ql\fi-283\li283\lin283\sb0\sa120\widctlpar\tql\tx283\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb50 \li600\fi-300 4.\tab
proof by construction; \par
\pard\plain\s46\ql\fi-283\li283\lin283\sb0\sa120\widctlpar\tql\tx283\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb50 \li600\fi-300 5.\tab
nonconstructive proof. \par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 {The contemporary} notion of proof is formalized and algorithmic. Around 1930 mathematicians could still hope for a \ldblquote mathematical theory of everything\rdblquote  which consists of a finite number of axioms and algorithmic derivation rules by which all true mathematical statements could formally be derived. In particular, as expressed in Hilbert\rquote s 2nd problem {hilbert-1900e}, it should be possible to prove the consistency of the axioms of arithmetic. Hence, Hilbert and other formalists dreamed, any such formal system (in German \ldblquote Kalk\'fcl\rdblquote ) consisting of axioms and derivation rules, might represent \ldblquote the essence of all mathematical truth.\rdblquote  This approach, as curageous as it appears, was doomed.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {G\'f6del}\~
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_godel1 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{54}{1931}{{G{\'f6}del}}{{}}}}}
], Tarski\~
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_tarski_32 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{128}{1932}{{Tarski}}{{}}}}}
], and Turing 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_turing_36 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{131}{1936-7 and 1937}{{{T}uring}}{{}}}}}
] put an end to the formalist program. They coded and formalized the concepts of proof and computation in general, equating them with algorithmic entities. Today, in times when universal computers are everywhere, this may seem no big deal; but in those days even coding was challenging \endash  in his proof of the undecidability of (Peano) arithmetic, G\'f6del used the uniqueness of prime decompositions to explicitly code mathematical formul\'e6! \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {For the sake} of exploring (algorithmically) these ideas let us consider the sketch of Turing\rquote s proof by contradiction of the unsolvability of the halting problem. The halting problem is about whether or not a computer will eventually halt on a given input, that is, will evolve into a state indicating the completion of a computation task or will stop altogether. Stated differently, a solution of the halting problem will be an algorithm that decides whether another arbitrary algorithm on arbitrary input will finish running or will run forever.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {\cf80 \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 The scheme of the proof by contradiction is as follows: the existence of a hypothetical halting algorithm capable of solving the halting problem will be {\i assumed.} This could, for instance, be a subprogram of some suspicious supermacro library that takes the code of an arbitrary program as input and outputs 1 or 0, depending on whether or not the program halts. One may also think of it as a sort of oracle or black box analyzing an arbitrary program in terms of its symbolic code and outputting one of two symbolic states, say, 1 or 0, referring to termination or nontermination of the input program, respectively.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 On the basis of this {\i hypothetical halting algorithm} one constructs another {\i diagonalization program} as follows: on receiving some arbitrary {\i input program} code as input, the {diagonalization program} consults the {\i hypothetical halting algorithm} to find out whether or not this {input program} halts; on receiving the answer, it does the {\i opposite:} If the hypothetical halting algorithm decides that the input program {\i halts,} the diagonalization program does {\i not halt} (it may do so easily by entering an infinite loop). Alternatively, if the hypothetical halting algorithm decides that the input program does {\i not halt,} the {diagonalization program} will {\i halt} immediately.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 The {diagonalization program} can be forced to execute a paradoxical task by receiving {\i its own program code} as input. This is so because, by considering the {diagonalization program,} the {hypothetical halting algorithm} steers the {diagonalization program} into {\i halting} if it discovers that it {\i does not halt;} conversely, the {hypothetical halting algorithm} steers the {diagonalization program} into {\i not halting} if it discovers that it {\i halts.}\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 The complete contradiction obtained in applying the {\i diagonalization program} to its own code proves that this program and, in particular, the {hypothetical halting algorithm} cannot exist.\par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 A universal computer can in principle be embedded into, or realized by, certain physical systems designed to universally compute. Assuming unbounded space and time, it follows by reduction that there exist physical observables, in particular, forecasts about whether or not an embedded computer will ever halt in the sense sketched earlier, that are provably undecidable.\par
