\pard\plain\s2\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs40\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 Numbers and sets of numbers\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 {The concept of numbering the universe} is far from trivial. In particular it is far from trivial which number schemes are appropriate. In the pythagorean tradition the natural numbers appear to be most natural. Actually Leibnitz (among others like Bacon before him) argues that just two number, say, \ldblquote {}\rdblquote  and \ldblquote {},\rdblquote  are enough to creat all of them.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {Every primary empirical evidence} seems to be based on some click in a detector: either there is some click or there is none. Thus every empirical physical evidence is composed from such elementary events.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 Thus binary number codes are in good, albeit somewhat accidential, accord with the intuition of most experimentalists today. I call it \ldblquote accidential\rdblquote  because quantum mechanics does not favour any base; the only criterium is the number of mutually exclusive measurement outcomes which determines the dimension of the linear vector space used for the quantum description model \endash  two mutually exclusive outcomes would result in a Hilbert space of dimension two, three mutually exclusive outcomes would result in a Hilbert space of dimension three, and so on.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {There are,} of course, many other sets of numbers imagined so far; all of which can be considered to be encodable by binary digits. One of the most challenging number schemes is that to the real numbers 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_drobot \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{41}{1964}{{Drobot}}{{}}}}}
]. It is totally different from the natural numbers insofar as there are undenumerably many reals; that is, it is impossible to find a one-to-one function \endash  a sort of \ldblquote translation\rdblquote  \endash  from the natural numbers to the reals.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 Cantor appears to be the first having realized this. In order to proof it, he invented what is today often called {\i Cantor\rquote s diagonalization technique,} or just diagonalization. It is a proof by contradiction; that is, what shall be disproved is assumed; and on the basis of this assumption a complete contradiction is derived.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {\cf80 \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 For the sake of contradiction, assume for the moment that the set of reals is denumerable. (This assumption will yield a contradiction.) That is, the enumeration is a one-to-one function {} (wrong), i.e., to any {} exists some {} and {\scaps0\b0\i vice versa}. No algorithmic restriction is imposed upon the enumeration, i.e., the enumeration may or may not be effectively computable. For instance, one may think of an enumeration obtained {\scaps0\b0\i via} the enumeration of computable algorithms and by assuming that {} is the output of the {}\rquote th algorithm. Let {} be the successive digits in the decimal expansion of {}. Consider now the {\i diagonal} of the array formed by successive enumeration of the reals, {\par
\pard\plain\s12\ql\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\tqc\tx3450\tqr\tx6900\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 \tab
\tab{\b0 (1)}\par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 yielding a new real number {}. Now, for the sake of contradiction, construct a new real {} by changing each one of these digits of {}, avoiding zero and nine in a decimal expansion. This is necessary because reals with different digit sequences are equal to each other if one of them ends with an infinite sequence of nines and the other with zeros, for example {}. The result is a real {} with {}, which differs from each one of the original numbers in at least one (i.e., in the \ldblquote diagonal\rdblquote ) position. Therefore, there exists at least one real which is not contained in the original enumeration, contradicting the assumption that {\i all} reals have been taken into account. Hence, {} is not denumerable.\par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 Bridgman has argued 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_bridgman \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{{29}{1934}{{Bridgman}}{{}}}}}
] that, from a physical point of view, such an argument is operationally unfeasible, because it is physically impossible to process an infinite enumeration; and subsequently, quasi on top of that, a digit switch. Alas, it is possible to recast the argument such that {} is finitely created up to arbitrary operational length, as the enumeration progresses.\par
